F. Student Instructional Matters
Subject
1. Vision 2020 Quality Schools in Every Neighborhood - Report on Student-Centered Coaching (LCAP Goal 1: Closing the Achievement Gap with High Expectations for All)
Meeting
May 15, 2018 - Regular Meeting, 5:00 p.m.
Type
Information

RECOMMENDATION: The Superintendent will provide information to the board and the public on LCAP Goal 1, Closing the Achievement Gap with High Expectations for All, focusing on student-centered coaching.

 

VISION 2020 Quality Indicator Destination: Every school is committed to maintaining high expectations for all students and to eliminating the persistent disparities in achievement and performance among student groups based on race, ethnicity, language or disability.  These disparities are understood as unacceptable and a focused plan of support is in place to eliminate the significant achievement gaps in order to realize academic proficiency for all students.  All relevant policies and practices reflect the goals of eliminating achievement disparities and attaining academic proficiency, explicitly and emphatically.  A districtwide focus and effort supports the advancement of high levels of student achievement by ensuring that every school is culturally competent, ensures uniformly high expectations, promotes rigorous curricula, differentiates instruction, and maximizes access for all students to high-level educational opportunities.  The district actively seeks to hire a diverse cadre of educators and administrators, as well as ensure proper emphasis on culturally responsive practices and regularly examines and monitors student achievement, policies, programs, tools and written documents to ensure that achievement gap goals are implemented.  All staff members understand how their respective positions contribute, directly or indirectly, to the implementation of the achievement gap goals.  Staff members understand and actively seek to learn the necessary knowledge and skills to serve diverse students and families.  Staff members assume responsibility for implementing plans that will address achievement disparities.  District and community stakeholders engage students and families, the private sector, faith-based groups, and higher education institutions to support district students in achieving academic proficiency.

 

LCAP Goal 1: All levels of the organization work to improve student achievement and close the achievement gap for all underperforming student groups.

 

Related LCAP Actions and Services:

  • 1.1.a.2. In moving toward a student-centered coaching model, central office instructional technology teachers will collaborate with other central office resource teachers, classroom teachers, and teacher teams around the use of digital tools for formative assessment.  Student-centered coaching includes setting specific targets for students that are rooted in the standards and curriculum and working collaboratively to ensure that targets are met.  Impact is measured based on student learning.
  • 1.5.a.6. Instructional technology staff will partner with central office resource teachers, classroom teachers, and teacher teams in student-centered coaching cycles to design differentiated and needs-based instruction using digital tools.  Collaboration may include co-planning and co-delivery of instruction and job-embedded professional development.
  • 1.7.a.7. Central office resource teachers and administrators will continue their work in support of the coaching and learning cycles at school sites to provide targeted feedback on best practices for students with disabilities to teachers, administrators, and Professional Learning Communities (PLC).
  • 1.8.a.2. During student-centered coaching cycles, focus on priority standards and proficiency scales for both Common Core and ELD Standards.
  • 1.8.b./c.1. In collaboration with area superintendents and Instructional Support Officers, OLA will identify schools with high percentages of English Learners (EL) and coordinate a student-centered coaching cycle to build teacher capacity to serve English Learners (EL) and record student progress.
  • 2.3.3. Coaching cycles will be strengthened across the district to ensure effective implementation of inclusive curriculum.
  • 5.1.a.4. FACE resource teachers will work with staff to develop and implement effective instructional coaching cycles that engage families (i.e., family strategies hoe visits, student-led conferencing, etc.) as a strategy to meet desired family engagement outcomes.

 

BACKGROUND: At regular, public board meetings Superintendent Marten provides reports that include the alignment of Vision 2020, the 12 Quality Indicators, and supporting LCAP actions, services and baseline data.  Following the Superintendent's Vision 2020/LCAP report, cluster and advisory groups, employee groups, and members of the public have the opportunity to engage in dialogue on the report and provide input and feedback on current LCAP implementation.  The complete LCAP document is available on the district website at https://www.sandiegounified.org/what-lcap.

 

[Originator/Contact:  Cindy Marten, Superintendent of Public Education, 619.725.5506]

3. Resolution Recognizing May 22, 2018, as Harvey Milk Day in San Diego Unified
Meeting
May 15, 2018 - Regular Meeting, 5:00 p.m.

Fiscal Impact
No

RECOMMENDATION: Approve the resolution recognizing May 22, 2018, as Harvey Milk Day in San Diego Unified.

 

BACKGROUND: Harvey Milk was born May 22, 1930, in Woodmere, New York.

 

Harvey served in the United States Navy during the Korean War as a diving officer aboard the submarine rescue ship USS Kittiwake and was later transferred to Naval Station, San Diego to serve as a diving instructor with the rank of Lieutenant.

 

Harvey was a tireless advocate of fairness for all Americans, both as a candidate for office and as a San Francisco Supervisor.

 

In 1977, Harvey was elected to the San Francisco Board of Supervisors, becoming the first openly gay man to be elected to public office in California. This milestone achievement gave hope to millions of gays and lesbians across the country that a day would come when they could live their lives openly and honestly without fear of discrimination.

 

As a Supervisor, Harvey worked with others to secure passage of San Francisco’s landmark Gay Rights Ordinance. This ordinance extended employment protections to gays and lesbians in San Francisco, and it became a model for anti-discrimination legislation throughout California and the nation.

 

In 1978, Harvey traversed the state to campaign against Proposition 6, which was known as the Briggs Initiative. Had it passed, Proposition 6 would have required California school districts to fire openly gay and lesbian teachers solely because of their sexual orientation. The proposition was defeated in the November 1978 election in part because Harvey successfully appealed to Californians’ basic sense of fairness.

 

Although Harvey’s life was cut short, he was a hero and role model, and his legacy of hope, tolerance, and equality lives on.

4. Resolution in Support of SB 1406 (Hill): Baccalaureate Degree Pilot Program
Meeting
May 15, 2018 - Regular Meeting, 5:00 p.m.
Type
Action (Consent)
Fiscal Impact
No

RECOMMENDATION: Approve Resolution in support of SB 1406: Baccalaureate Degree Pilot Program, to extend the state’s baccalaureate pilot program thereby allowing San Diego Unified students to continue participating in the pilot program.

 

BACKGROUND: The Board of Education of the San Diego Unified School District recognizes that a growing number of employers now require a bachelor’s degree in their job qualifications.

 

Students who are unable to be accommodated in California’s public universities due to lack of space or inadequate baccalaureate instruction in high-demand workforce fields are compelled to leave the state in order to obtain their degrees.

 

Community colleges are able to provide high-quality, accessible and affordable, local programs at the baccalaureate level.

 

In 2014 the California legislature passed SB 850 establishing the Baccalaureate Degree Pilot Program for 15 community colleges, including San Diego Mesa College.

 

The pilot program allowed community colleges to offer a bachelor’s degree program in a specific career/technical field, thereby delivering on the promise of creating greater access to four-year degrees for the state’s residents.

 

Current legislation includes an end date of 2023 for completion of the degree, meaning students cannot enroll in the pilot program after 2018 with sufficient time to complete their studies.

 

In order to allow more students to take advantage of the pilot program, Senator Jerry Hill has introduced Senate Bill 1406 which proposes an extension to the baccalaureate pilot program.

5. Resolution in Support of AB 1743 (O'Donnell): Career Technical Education Funding
Meeting
May 15, 2018 - Regular Meeting, 5:00 p.m.
Type
Action (Consent)
Fiscal Impact
No

RECOMMENDATION: Approve Resolution in support of AB 1743: Career Technical Education Funding, to provide permanent Career Technical Education funding thereby allowing San Diego Unified students to continue participating in College, Career and Technical Education programs.

 

BACKGROUND: Existing law establishes the California Career Technical Education Incentive Grant Program to encourage and maintain the delivery of career technical education (CTE) programs during implementation of the Local Control Funding Formula (LCFF).

 

CTE insures that competitive and skilled workers are ready, willing, and capable of holding jobs in high-wage, high-skill, and in-demand career fields such as science, technology, engineering, mathematics, nursing, allied health, construction, information technology, energy sustainability, and many other career fields that are vital in keeping California competitive in the global economy.

 

Throughout the nation, studies show students in high-quality rigorous CTE programs have lower truancy and dropout rates and increased student graduation.

 

The San Diego Unified College, Career and Technical Education (CCTE) program provides college and career themed programs that integrate core standards and industry competencies with real-world applications that prepare our students for success.

 

Without sustained, dedicated CTE funding, successful regional and center-based CTE programs are at risk as local cost pressures and priorities threaten the viability of these programs to be offered or expanded.

 

Assembly Bill 1743 would instead require dedicated and permanent funding for high-quality CTE programs to allow schools to sustain a well-educated and skilled workforce.

Preuss was designed as an intensive college preparatory educational environment for students from low income families who represent the first generation in their families to graduate from a four-year college or university. To support students, the school offers a single-track college prep curriculum, small classes, tutor-assisted teaching, community mentors, and weekly professional development.

 

The University Prep Advisory enables students and parents to be guided and supported by the same teacher from sixth grade to graduation. Preuss has a longer school year (198 days), a longer school day (6 hours, 32 minutes of instructional time), and utilizes block scheduling.

**END SECTION**

 

Preuss is seeking renewal of its charter for a five-year term beginning July 1, 2018 and ending June 30, 2023. Staff recommends that the board grant the charter renewal with the following clarifications as noted:

 

1. Revise the English Language Learners section as detailed below:

 

By July 15, 2018, Preuss will submit a revised English Language Learner section that includes specific information regarding criteria that the school uses to reclassify students, and the monitoring that Preuss does after a student is reclassified.

 

2. Revise the Special Education section as detailed below:

 

By July 15, 2018, Preuss will submit a revised Special Education section that includes the following specific information:

  • A statement that the school will comply with all applicable state and federal laws in serving students with disabilities, including, but not limited to, IDEA, Section 504, Title II of the Americans with Disabilities Act, and any other law enforced by the Office of Civil Rights (OCR).

  • The process Preuss uses to identify, refer and assess students for special education services, including required timelines.

  • Information regarding when IEP meetings and reviews will be done.

  • The process to be used for interim IEP’s at the charter school.

  • The process to be used for providing parents with the Notice of Procedural Safeguards, and dispute resolution.

  • Identify what services (including specialized services) will be provided on site for special education students.

  • A statement that a change in SELPA membership requires a material revision.

 

3. Revise the Health and Safety section as detailed below:

 

The following paragraph will be added:

 

Preuss shall comply with Education Code Section 49414 for emergency epinephrine auto-injectors.

 

4. Revise the Admission Requirements section as detailed below:

 

By July 15, 2018, Preuss will submit a revised Admission Requirements section which reflects compliance with Ed Code section 47605(d). This section states in relevant part:

 

“In addition to any other requirement imposed under this part, a charter school shall be nonsectarian in its programs, admission policies, employment practices, and all other operations, shall not charge tuition, and shall not discriminate against a pupil on the basis of the characteristics listed in Section 220…”

 

“A charter school shall admit all pupils who wish to attend the charter school.”

 

“If the number of pupils who wish to attend the charter school exceeds the charter school’s capacity, attendance…shall be determined by a public random drawing. Preference shall be extended to pupils currently attending the charter school and pupils who reside in the school district…Priority order for any preference shall be determined in the charter petition…”

 

Historically, the admission process at Preuss has required students to meet three “prequalifying” criteria in order to be entered into the school’s public random drawing (“lottery”). This resulted in some applicants not being included in the lottery process, as summarized in the following table.

5. Revise the Audits section as detailed below:

 

The Preuss School UC San Diego has contracted with an accounting firm with K‐12 expertise and obtains, annually, an independent annual financial audit that is conducted in accordance with generally accepted accounting principles applicable to UC or to The Preuss School UC San Diego, if different. The external auditor has full access to records and systems of the School. The University appoints an internal auditor to act as liaison between the external auditor and the University’s General Accounting personnel so that records relevant to the School may be obtained as needed. The University Administrator and Treasurer review the financial audit. Audit results, including findings, exceptions, or deficiencies, are brought to the attention of The Preuss School UC San Diego and the Board of Directors through the Board’s Finance Subcommittee. Each finding is addressed accordingly in writing by the School’s Principal and Business Manager and resolved to the satisfaction of the district as required by Ed Code section 47605(b)(5)(I), within 180 days, and then sent to the District, SDCOE and CDE. They are responsible for creating and implementing internal controls or systems that resolve issues highlighted in the audit process and provide follow‐up reports as necessary to those agencies.

 

6. Revise the Retirement Programs section as detailed below:

 

State Teachers Retirement System (STRS) provides concurrent retirement benefits with UCRS. There are only two certificated employees who have been “grandfathered in” for STRS. All other employees participate solely in the UCRS. The Public Employees Retirement System (PERS) shares reciprocity agreement with UCRS.

 

7. Revise the Dispute Resolution section as detailed below:

 

In the event of a dispute between The Preuss School UC San Diego and the District regarding the terms of this charter or any other issue regarding the School and District relationship, both parties agree to apprise the other, in writing, of the specific disputed issue(s). For disputes governed by other agreements between The Preuss School and the District, the appropriate agreement shall govern the dispute resolution process. In the event the initiating party District believes the dispute relates to an issue that could potentially lead to revocation of the charter, the district agrees to this shall be specifically noted that possibility in the written dispute statement, unless there is a severe and imminent threat to student health or safety. California Code of Regulations section 11968.5.2 shall govern charter revocation. Within 30 days of sending written notice of a dispute, or longer if both parties agree, a School representative, a District representative, or their designees, shall meet and confer in an attempt to resolve the dispute. If this meeting fails to resolve the dispute, two representatives from each organization shall meet again at the earliest mutually convenient date to attempt to resolve the dispute. If this joint meeting fails to resolve the dispute, The Preuss School UC San Diego representative and the District representative shall meet again within 15 days, or longer if both parties agree, to identify a neutral, third‐party mediator to assist in dispute resolution (“Mediation”). The format of the Mediation shall be developed jointly by the representatives and shall incorporate informal rules of evidence and procedure unless both parties agree otherwise. Unless jointly agreed, the Mediation shall conclude within 45 days. Each party shall bear their own costs associated with dispute resolution, including attorneys’ fees, and shall bear one‐half the costs of the Mediation.

 

In the event the Mediation does not result in resolution of the dispute, both parties agree to continue good faith negotiations until they mutually agree that mutual resolution is not possible. If the District reasonably determines that The Preuss School UC San Diego is in violation of the charter so as to constitute a severe and imminent threat to the health and safety of the School’s students, then the dispute need not be referred to mediation and : (1) the parties’ representatives shall immediately meet and confer in an attempt to remedy the alleged violation and if the parties cannot promptly resolve the issue, the District reserves the right to take any action it deems reasonably necessary and The Preuss School UC San Diego reserves the right to seek legal redress for any such actions under the law; (2) the dispute need not be referred to Mediation.

 

When considering a petition for renewal, pursuant to Title 5 of the California Code of Regulations section 11966.4(b)(1), the district governing board shall consider the past performance of the school’s academics, finances, and operations in evaluating the likelihood of future success, along with future plans for improvement, if any.

 

Staff has visited Preuss annually. The annual site visit includes document review, classroom observations, and interviews of charter board members, teachers, administrators, financial managers, parents, and/or students. During the annual site visit, as well as throughout the year, the areas of academics, finances, and operations are monitored as part of the district’s oversight duties.

 

ACADEMICS

 

As the charter granting authority, pursuant to Education Code section 47607(a)(3)(A), the district shall consider increases in pupil academic achievement for all groups of pupils served by the charter school as the most important factor in determining whether to grant a charter renewal.

 

Per Education Code section 47607(b), a charter school shall meet at least one of the following criteria before receiving a renewal:

  1. Attained its Academic Performance Index (API) growth target in the prior year or in two of the last three years both schoolwide and for all groups of pupils served by the charter school.

  2. Ranked in deciles 4 to 10, inclusive, on the API in the prior year or in two of the last three years.

  3. Ranked in deciles 4 to 10, inclusive, on the API for a demographically comparable school in the prior year or in two of the last three years.

  4. The entity that granted the charter determines that the academic performance of the charter school is at least equal to the academic performance of the public schools that the charter school pupils would otherwise have been required to attend, as well as the academic performance of the schools in the school district in which the charter school is located, taking into account the composition of the pupil population that is served at the charter school.

  5. Qualified for an alternative accountability system pursuant to Education Code section 52052(g).

     

    Assembly Bill (“AB”) 484 amended Education Code sections 52052(e)(2)(F) and 52052(e)(4) to allow schools that do not have an API calculated in 2013–14 through 2016-17 to use one of the following criteria to meet legislative and/or programmatic requirements:

  1. The most recent API calculation;

  2. An average of the three most recent annual API calculations; or

  3. Alternative measures that show increases in pupil academic achievement for all groups of pupils schoolwide and among significant groups. The decision to use one of these criteria may be made on a program by program basis and is a local decision.

Staff is concerned regarding the content of the LCAP and the annual update. As reflected in Tables 18 and 19, some of the “Goals” do not contain any actual goals. For example, goals 3-8 appear to be the titles of state priorities. The LCAP Instructions indicate that the goal “is a broad statement that describes the desired result to which all actions/services are directed. A goal answers the question: What is the LEA seeking to achieve.”

 

In the “Expected” measurable outcomes section of the annual update, the school has listed several items, but there are no identified metrics or indicators that the school uses to track progress toward the expected outcome. For example, Goal 8 includes an expected outcome of “improve suspension and expulsion rates,” but there is no indication of what the current rate is, or what rate the school is attempting to reach. The “Actual” measurable outcomes sections for every goal contain no updates on progress, as the only information included says “as expected.” It is unclear if progress has been made toward the goals.

 

Table 19 includes the four pages which make up the school’s 2017-18 LCAP. Rather than doing each goal separately, the school opted to “combine” its nine goals into two pages. Both pages have the same Expected Annual Measurable Outcomes of 1) graduation rate, 2) college acceptance rate, and 3) college enrollment rate. The LCAP Instructions indicate that the expected annual measurable outcomes should identify the metrics or indicators that will be used to track progress toward the expected outcomes. The listed outcomes do not appear to specifically relate to some of the goals, such as school climate or parental engagement. In the “Planned Actions/Services” section, Preuss wrote, ”[s]ee actions under goals in current year LCAP.” It is unclear what the school is referring to in this section. The current year LCAP is the four pages included as table 19, and there are no actions included in the goals section. If the school is referring to the Annual Update section it would be concerning that there were no new actions or services planned for 2017-18.

H. Operational Matters Reserved for the Board
Subject
3. Resolution in Support of Healthy Start Times for All High School Students (Evans/Beiser)
Meeting
May 15, 2018 - Regular Meeting, 5:00 p.m.
Type
Action

RECOMMENDATION: Adopt resolution in support of healthy start times for all high school students.  The resolution provides that,

  • The Board is committed to transitioning to Healthy Start Times as outlined by the American Academy of Pediatrics, the American Medical Association, the National Sleep Foundation, the American Psychological Association and other scientific research organizations.
  • Planning for Healthy Start Times be completed during the 2018-19 school year so that first period online course options for high school students will be offered to as many students as possible in the 2019-20 school year.
  • Because the above will not provide benefit equally to all students, especially those who must travel by bus, that by 2020-21 the agreed upon Healthy Start Times shall be implemented at all San Diego Unified School District high schools.

 

FULL TEXT OF RESOLUTION

Two-thirds of teenagers are sleep deprived with significant consequences to students’ physical, mental and emotional health and academic achievement.

 

The Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, the American Academy of Pediatrics, the American Medical Association, the National Sleep Foundation, the American Psychological Association and other scientific research organizations have called for secondary schools to start no earlier than 8:30 a.m.

 

Studies have shown that healthy start times have resulted in students getting significantly more sleep and improved attendance, decreased tardiness, decreased incidents of discipline, improved student achievement and reduced accidents, as well as improvements to physical and emotional health.

 

The San Diego Unified Board has indicated its agreement in principle with healthy start times in our October 2017 action calling for school communities to begin the conversation.

 

All change is difficult and no school schedule (early or late) matches up with parents’ work schedules.

 

Last year Senate Bill 328 (school start times, pupil attendance) passed the Senate and subsequently passed the Assembly Education Committee, but failed to garner enough votes to pass the full Assembly and is likely to continue resurfacing in the legislature, just as the mandatory vaccination bill passed for the benefit of students’ health.

 

Change to successfully implement Healthy Start Times requires input from parents, teachers, staff, students, health and wellness, labor relations, transportation, finance, athletics and other stakeholders to work out the logistics.

 

The Board is committed to transitioning to Healthy Start Times as outlined by the American Academy of Pediatrics, the American Medical Association, the National Sleep Foundation, the American Psychological Association and other scientific research organizations.

 

Planning for Healthy Start Times be completed during the 2018-19 school year so that first period online course options for high school students will be offered to as many students as possible in the 2019-20 school year.

 

Because the above will not provide benefit equally to all students, especially those who must travel by bus, that by 2020-21 the agreed upon Healthy Start Times shall be implemented at all San Diego Unified School District high schools.

 

FISCAL IMPACT: None at this time.  Potential financial impact in 2019-20 and 2020-21.

 

PRIOR YEAR FISCAL IMPACT: None.

 

IMPACT TO DISTRICT STAFFING: None at this time. Potential staffing impact in 2019-20 and 2020-21.

 

CONSULTATION WITH BOARD ADVISORY COMMITTEE: Not applicable.

 

BACKGROUND:  On October 10, 2017 the Board approved Board Trustees John Lee Evans and Sharon Whitehurst-Payne's proposal to direct the Superintendent to begin an investigation on the possibility of a later start time, 8:30 a.m. or later, for secondary schools, beginning with high schools.  See staff informational update on school start times at item F2, Update on School Start Times.

 

 

[Originator/Contact:  Board Trustees John Lee Evans and Kevin Beiser, board@sandi.net, 619.725.5550]

1. Public Hearing and Resolution Increasing School Facility Fees Pursuant to Education Code Section 17620 and Determination that the Adoption of Such Fees is Exempt from Further Environmental Review Pursuant to Education Code Section 17621; BUDGETED: YES, REAL ESTATE DEVELOPER FEE FUNDS
Meeting
May 15, 2018 - Regular Meeting, 5:00 p.m.
Type
Action, Public Hearing
Fiscal Impact
Yes
Dollar Amount
$50.00
Budgeted
Yes
Budget Source
Real Estate Developer Fee Funds

RECOMMENDATION: Conduct Public Hearing and Adopt Resolution Increasing School Facility Fees (Attachment 1). The revisions include adjustment for inflation of the residential project fee upward from $3.48 to $3.79 per square foot and a similar adjustment of the commercial/industrial project fee from $0.56 to $0.61 per square foot. Approval of this item by the Board will cause the fees to increase 60 days following its adoption.

 

FISCAL IMPACT: $50.00-NOE Filing Fee; Budget String: 5498-02501-00-5842-8200-0000-25001-0000.

 

PRIOR YEAR FISCAL IMPACT: None.

 

IMPACT TO DISTRICT STAFFING: None.

 

CONSULTATION WITH BOARD ADVISORY COMMITTEE: Not applicable.

 

BACKGROUND: California Education Code Section 17620 allows the governing board of any school district to levy fees against construction within the boundaries of the school district for the purpose of funding construction or reconstruction of school facilities. San Diego Unified School District (District) has collected impact fees as authorized under Education Code Section 17620 since 1987.

 

The State Allocation Board (SAB) announces the Level 1 fees every two years in January on the even years. On January 24, 2018, the SAB authorized an increase in the maximum Level 1 fees per square foot as follows: Up to $3.79 per square foot of assessable space of new residential construction and up to $.61 per square foot of chargeable covered and enclosed commercial/industrial space.

 

The District is required to complete a justification study in order to continue to collect the fees. Schoolhouse Services completed a comprehensive Fees Justification Study for the District in March of 2017. Following the State Allocation Board announcement in January, 2018, Schoolhouse Services formally reviewed the Fee Justification Study and issued a Review of Fee Justification Documentation (Attachment 2) on April 10, 2018, indicating the District qualifies to continue to levy Level 1 School Impact Fees at the SAB newly authorized rate of $3.79 per square foot of residential construction and $.61 per square foot of commercial/industrial space.

 

This Board-adopted resolution for levying fees on development projects pursuant to Education Code Section 17620 is required to increase the fees as approved by the State Allocation Board. The revisions include adjustment for inflation of the residential project fee upward from $3.48 to $3.79 per square foot and a similar adjustment of the commercial/industrial project fee from $0.56 to $0.61 per square foot. Approval of this item by the Board will cause the fees to increase 60 days following its adoption.

 

Environmental Review: Education Code section 17621 specifically exempts the adoption, increase, or imposition of any fee, charge, dedication or other requirement pursuant to Education Code section 17620 from the provisions of the California Environmental Quality Act (“CEQA”), (Public Resources Code Section 21000 et seq.). On October 10, 2017, the Board determined that an increase in school facility fees is exempt from further environmental review under CEQA pursuant to Education Code Sections 17621 and staff filed a notice of exemption with the San Diego County Recorder/Clerk on October 13, 2017. Staff has prepared a new Notice of Exemption for the adoption of the increased fees identified in the Resolution (Attachment 3). Upon Board approval, staff is directed to file the Notice of Exemption with the San Diego County Recorder/Clerk.

 

[Originator/Contact: Lee Dulgeroff, Chief, Facilities Planning and Construction, 858.637.3516, ldulgeroff@sandi.net and Gene Fuller, Director, Real Estate, Office of the Chief, Facilities Planning and Construction, 619.278.6724, gfuller@sandi.net]

RECOMMENDATION: Approve Declaration of Need for Fully Qualified Educators, effective July 1, 2018 through June 30, 2019, submitted to the California Commission on Teacher Credentialing (CCTC) by county offices of education, public school districts, state-wide agencies, or non-public schools/agencies.

 

FISCAL IMPACT: None.

 

PRIOR YEAR FISCAL IMPACT: None.

 

IMPACT TO DISTRICT STAFFING: None.

 

CONSULTATION WITH BOARD ADVISORY COMMITTEE: Not applicable.

 

BACKGROUND: The California Commission on Teacher Credentialing (CCTC) requires that under Education Code Section 44300, local boards of education annually adopt a Declaration of Need for Fully Qualified Educators and an authorizing resolution in the form of a motion, prior to employing teachers on emergency permits. The Declaration requires the district estimate the number, type, and subject of emergency permits that may be needed for the ensuing school year and to provide information about recruitment activities that have been conducted in the effort to employ or train fully-credentialed teachers.

 

The district utilizes emergency permits in designated subject fields such as special education and bilingual Mandarin or French. Emergency permits are only utilized after a diligent search to recruit a fully-prepared teacher is made, and a suitable fully-prepared teacher is not available to the school district.

 

The Declaration of Need must be adopted by the governing board of the school district before filing documents with the CCTC; therefore this declaration is submitted for approval.

BACKGROUND: The proposed project includes the installation of 13 portable and relocatable classroom buildings, one portable administration building, and one relocatable restroom building on the Twain High School campus located at 6402 Linda Vista Rd, San Diego, CA 92111. Additional site work includes the provision of asphalt pads/foundations and all utilities for each portable and relocatable building, as well as minor trenching for utility connections. The portable and relocatable buildings would accommodate a new charter high school on a portion of the existing Twain High School campus. The proposed student enrollment associated with the new charter high school would be approximately 380 students at buildout.

 

Proposition 39 (Education Code section 47614) requires the district to offer reasonably equivalent facilities to charter schools that show that they are eligible to receive such facilities. At its January 23, 2018 meeting, the board approved district staff recommendations for the preliminary offers of facilities to eligible charter schools that made appropriate applications for facilities under the provisions of California Education Code section 47614 and California Code of Regulations, title 5, sections 11969 et seq. (Regulations), which require: 1) that districts must submit a final offer of facilities to eligible charter schools on or before April 2, and 2) that the charter school must respond to the final offer by May 1, if they intend to receive district facilities for the upcoming year. Thrive Public Schools agreed in writing on March 2, 2018 to extend the timeline to May 16, 2018 and June 18, 2018, respectively.

 

Subsequently, staff analyzed the request in conformity with the requirements of Education Code section 47614 and the implementing regulations and developed recommendations for the final offer of facilities for eligible charters. Staff is submitting this report and its recommendations for board approval and requests the board to adopt the report as its statement of reasons.

ENVIRONMENTAL REVIEW: On March 23, 2018, the District made the draft Negative Declaration (ND) available for a 20-day review at the following locations: San Diego Unified School District, Physical Plant Operations Center, Annex Room 5, 4860 Ruffner Street, San Diego, CA 92111; Linda Vista Branch Public Library, 2160 Ulric Street, San Diego, CA 92111; Twain Main High School Office, 6402 Linda Vista Road, San Diego, California 92111; and online via the District's website. The Draft Initial Study/ND evaluated the following environmental issues: aesthetics, agriculture and forestry resources, air quality, biological resources, cultural resources, geology and soils, greenhouse gas emissions, hazards and hazardous materials, hydrology and water quality, land use and planning, mineral resources, noise, population and housing, public services, recreation, transportation/traffic, tribal cultural resources, and utilities and service systems. There are no mitigation measures necessary to reduce potential significant environmental impacts to less than significant.
 

Eighteen comment letters were received from State Agencies and citizens in response to the issuance of the Draft IS/ND. The comment letters raised several issues of concern regarding the Proposed Project and its potential effect on the surrounding community including (but not limited to):

  • Site specific drainage and erosion issues.

BACKGROUND: In an effort to continue the improvement of procedures and processes for centralized procurement and contracting district-wide, a new process will be implemented for streamlining Independent Contractor Agreements. The goal is to limit and reduce the number of contracted service items that are included in this item for approval via the ratification process. Ratification is an after-the-fact request for the board to approve services already provided or being provided at the time the Independent Contractors Agreement (ICA) is presented for approval.

 

Executive Leadership should work with requestors to reduce and eliminate the need for ratified ICA's. Effective immediately, after an ICA is submitted to and approved by the respective Executive Leadership/Instructional Cabinet team member, it will then be sent to the Strategic Sourcing and Contracts Department. The ICA will include a requisition number that pre-encumbers the funding for payment of the ICA after services are completed.

RECOMMENDATION: Approve Agreement with Pearson Education, Inc. for the acquisition of EnVision Math 2.0, 2016 materials for the 2018-19 school year (GD-18-0857-18). The term of this Agreement is May 16, 2018 through June 30, 2021.

 

FISCAL IMPACT: Total not-to-exceed amount: $900,000.00. Budget string: 5458-63000-00-4101-1000-1110-01000-6231.

 

PRIOR YEAR FISCAL IMPACT: For the period July 1, 2016 through May 15, 2018: $2,001,330.00.

CONSULTATION WITH BOARD ADVISORY COMMITTEE: Not applicable.

 

BACKGROUND: On April 3, 2018, the board authorized the purchase of district-adopted and supplemental instructional materials and textbooks for the 2018-19 school year to ensure that sufficient standards-aligned textbooks and/or instructional materials are available to each pupil in accordance with Education Code Section 60119 and in compliance with Williams Settlement Legislation.

 

The district moved to CCSS 2012 Version of K-2 student materials in the 2013-14 school year, but continued use of the California version for Grades 3-5. The district has since expanded CCSS enVision Math to elementary Grades K-5 with the updated 2016 CCSS version of the adopted enVision Math program. The updated version has been reviewed by Leadership and Learning Department curriculum-area experts and teachers and supports the district’s vision. The move to CCSS enVision Math 2.0, 2016 provides consumable student texts for Grades K-5.

 

The curriculum has a very strong problem-solving component which aligns perfectly with launch, explore, summarize and guides teachers how to summarize the problem-solving component including sample student work. Within the pacing, there will be days to incorporate the conceptual-based tasks that many teachers love about the concept guides. This curriculum is Promethean board friendly. Another strength of the new curriculum is the online testing component in which students can take end-of-topic tests online with items that are similar to SBAC (Smarter Balanced Assessment Consortium) items and are much better than the Illuminate items. There is also the ability to collect the data to use it to inform instruction. 

 

Pearson/Scott Foresman-Addison Wesley is the exclusive publisher of its enVision Math product. Given the unique needs of the district and the single source from which the district can obtain the required materials, the board finds that the needs of the district are best served by acquiring the product as a sole source procurement of materials.

RECOMMENDATION:

Approve the appointment of the following district employee to San Diego Adult Education Regional Consortium (SDAERC), effective July 1, 2018.  This is a requirement enacted by Assembly Bill 104.  The term of this appointment is ongoing until otherwise designated by the Board of Education.

  • Al Love, Director, College, Career and Technical Education, San Diego Unified School District

 

FISCAL IMPACT: None

 

PRIOR YEAR FISCAL IMPACT: None

 

IMPACT TO DISTRICT STAFFING: None

 

CONSULTATION WITH BOARD ADVISORY COMMITTEE: Not applicable.

 

BACKGROUND:

Assembly Bill 104, Article 9 outlines the Adult Education Block Grant Program which includes $500 million in Position 98 General Fund revenue as part of the Adult Education Block Grant package (Fund 11).  In order to receive this funding, each adult education region throughout the state must have established a regional adult education consortium with representatives from each member district serving on the consortium.  These official representatives must be designated by each member’s governing board.  San Diego Unified School District and San Diego Community College District make up membership of the San Diego Adult Education Regional Consortium (SDAERC).
 

The main functions of the consortium are for their members to collaboratively work together to identify the needs of the adult learner population in the region; to develop an annual regional plan to best meet the identified needs; and to approve and submit, the California Department of Education and the California Community College Chancellor’s Office, a distribution schedule that includes the amount of Adult Education Block Grant apportionment that is to be distributed to each consortium member for each fiscal year, as determined by the Adult Education Regional Plan.

Budgeted
Yes
Budget Source
Various Funds

RECOMMENDATION: Approve the Accept, Budget, and Spend Income Summary for March 2018.

 

FISCAL IMPACT: $5,406,212.00.

 

PRIOR YEAR FISCAL IMPACT: None. 

 

IMPACT TO DISTRICT STAFFING: None. 

 

CONSULTATION WITH BOARD ADVISORY COMMITTEE: Not applicable.

 

BACKGROUND:

 

Actions to accept, budget, and spend income, in excess of that included in the adopted budget, are authorized by Education Code Section 42602. These actions provide the means by which the board of education can access income which becomes available to them after they have adopted a final budget. When such added income is available and a majority of the board is in agreement as to its use, the action to accept, budget, and spend the income is a routine action. It increases the budgeted appropriations in the amount of the added income and authorizes the expenditure of that income for the purposes designated in the resolution and supporting budget.

 

[Originator/Contact: Candi Lukat, Controller, Office of the Chief Business Officer, (619) 725-7171, clukat@sandi.net]

30. Determination that Lease with San Diego French American School is Exempt from Further Environmental Review Under the California Environmental Quality Act (CEQA) Pursuant to CEQA Guidelines Sections 15301, 15304 and 15314; Resolution of Intent to Lease Real Property and Improvements; and Approval of Lease Agreement with San Diego French American School at Former Decatur Elementary Site; BUDGETED; YES, REVENUE, PROPERTY LEASE
Meeting
May 15, 2018 - Regular Meeting, 5:00 p.m.
Type
Action (Consent)
Fiscal Impact
Yes
Dollar Amount
$41,446,278.38
Budgeted
Yes
Budget Source
Revenue, Property Lease

RECOMMENDATION: Determine that the Lease Agreement (Lease) with San Diego French American School (SDFAS) at former Decatur Elementary is exempt from further environmental review under the California Environmental Quality Act (CEQA) and direct District staff to file a Notice of Exemption (NOE, Attachment 1); Approve Lease with SDFAS at former Decatur Elementary (SV18-0957-99, Attachment 2); and Approve Resolution of Intent to Lease Real Property and Improvements (Attachment 3). Term of the Lease is July 1, 2018 through June 30, 2058.

 

FISCAL IMPACT: Revenue $41,446,278.38 (40 Year Lease); Revenue of total Lease value over 40 years will not be less than $41,446,328.38 (based on a minimum of 3% annual increases which could be greater if the Consumer Price Index is higher than 3%). $6,000,000.00 of this revenue to be prepaid by SDFAS by June 1, 2018. Due to this prepayment of rent, no monthly rent will be collected until July 1, 2024.

*District to pay $50.00 filing fee for San Diego County Recorder/Clerk for the CEQA compliance relating to this Lease;

Budget String: 5498-04003-00-8650-0000-0000-40003-0000 / Property Management Funds.

 

PRIOR YEAR FISCAL IMPACT: Revenue $451,452.12.

 

IMPACT TO DISTRICT STAFFING: None.

 

CONSULTATION WITH BOARD ADVISORY COMMITTEE: Not Applicable.

 

BACKGROUND: On February 28, 2006, the Board approved a lease between SDFAS and District for a portion of the former Decatur Elementary School Site from September 1, 2006 through August 31, 2011 with one, five-year option to extend. Amendments clarifying square footage of premises and modifying alteration provisions to that lease were approved by the Board on July 19, 2006 and March 17, 2007. SDFAS exercised their option to extend the term to September 1, 2011 through August 31, 2016 and a Third Amendment was approved by the Board on June 28, 2011, which gave SDFAS an additional five-year option to extend. That option was exercised by SDFAS on August 28, 2015 thereby extended their term through August 31, 2021.

 

On April 25, 2017, the Board authorized District staff to submit a waiver request to the State Board of Education (SBE) regarding Education Code requirements for lease of surplus property. This waiver was approved by SBE on July 13, 2017, and allowed the District to directly negotiate a new lease with SDFAS, as the existing tenant.

 

The negotiations with SDFAS are now complete. This new Lease is necessary in order for the District to:

  1. Terminate the existing lease which is set to expire August 31, 2021.
  2. Establish a new term beginning July 1, 2018 through June 30, 2058 with two, 10-year options to extend.
  3. Obtain a one-time prepayment of rent of $6,000,000 due by June 1, 2018. This prepayment of rent covers the period of July 1, 2018 through June 30, 2024.
  4. Receive monthly rent payments of $51,667.67 commencing July 1, 2024. Rent will increase annually by the Consumer Price Index or 3% whichever is greater.

Before ordering the lease of any property, this Resolution of Intent to Lease Real Property and Improvements pursuant to Education Code section 17466 is required to be adopted by the Board with a two-thirds vote. District staff shall post this resolution in three (3) public places within the District’s boundaries in compliance with Education Code section 17469 as revised per the waiver approved by SBE.

 

Reasons Why Project is Exempt from CEQA: The proposed activity is a project subject to CEQA. However, it is exempt from further environmental review under the following CEQA categorical exemption classes:

 

Existing Facilities (Class 1) - Class 1 consists of the operation, repair, maintenance, permitting, leasing, licensing, or minor alteration of existing public or private structures, facilities, mechanical equipment, or topographical features, involving negligible or no expansion of use beyond that existing at the time of the lead agency‘s determination (CEQA Guidelines §15301).

 

The Proposed Project includes the execution of a new lease agreement, repairs to existing facilities, and the installation of one modular classroom, which would result in negligible expansion of use beyond existing conditions (see discussion under Class 14 exemption below). Therefore, the application of a Class 1 categorical exemption is appropriate for the Proposed Project.

 

Minor Alterations to Land (Class 4) - Class 4 consists of minor public or private alterations in the condition of land, water, and/or vegetation which do not involve removal of healthy, mature, scenic trees except for forestry or agricultural purposes. (CEQA Guidelines §15304).

 

The Proposed Project may include minor trenching for underground utilities. All trenching would occur within previously paved and/or disturbed areas and would not extend off-site into any undisturbed or environmentally sensitive areas. Alteration of the land would not involve the removal of any healthy, mature, scenic trees and all disturbed areas associated with the trenching work would be restored upon completion of the Proposed Project. Therefore, the application of a Class 4 categorical exemption is appropriate for the Proposed Project.

 

Minor Additions to Schools (Class 14) - Class 14 consists of minor additions to existing schools within existing school grounds where the addition does not increase original student capacity by more than 25% or ten classrooms, whichever is less. The addition of portable classrooms is included in this exemption (CEQA Guidelines §15314).

 

The Proposed Project would install one new modular classroom building with a maximum capacity of 30 students. This would increase the site capacity from 640 students to 670, an increase of less than five percent. Therefore, the application of a Class 14 categorical exemption is appropriate for the Proposed Project.

 

Exceptions to Use of a Categorical Exemption (CEQA Guidelines Section 15300.2): Section 15300.2 of the State CEQA Guidelines specifies several exceptions to the use of a categorical exemption.

  1. Location. Classes 3, 4, 5, 6, and 11 are qualified by consideration of where the project is to be located – a project that is ordinarily insignificant in its impact on the environment may in a particularly sensitive environment be significant. Therefore, these classes are considered to apply in all instances, except where the project may impact on an environmental resource of hazardous or critical concern where designated, precisely mapped, and officially adopted pursuant to law by federal, state, or local agencies.
  2. Cumulative Impact. All exemptions for these classes are inapplicable when the cumulative impact of successive projects of the same type in the same place over time is significant.
  3. Significant Effect. A categorical exemption shall not be used for an activity where there is a reasonable possibility that the activity will have a significant effect on the environment due to unusual circumstances.
  4. Scenic Highways. A categorical exemption shall not be used for a project which may result in damage to scenic resources, including but not limited to, trees, historic buildings, rock outcroppings, or similar resources within a highway officially designated as a state scenic highway. This does not apply to improvements that are required as mitigation by an adopted negative declaration or certified EIR.
  5. Hazardous Waste Sites. A categorical exemption shall not be used for a project located on a site that is included on any list compiled pursuant to Section 65962.5 of the Government Code.
  6. Historical Resources. A categorical exemption shall not be used for a project that may cause a substantial adverse change in the significance of a historical resource.

 

The following provides review of the potential environmental issues associated with the Proposed Project to ensure that the above exceptions are not relevant to the project.

  1. Location. The Proposed Project would occur entirely within the boundaries of an existing school in an urbanized community. The site has been developed as a school since 1960 and all areas on the school are either paved or disturbed, and therefore are not environmentally sensitive. Surrounding land uses consist of residential or residential serving land uses. However, the Proposed Project would not extend into any offsite areas. Therefore, this exception does not apply to the project.
  2. Cumulative Impact. There are no known future projects proposed on the school site or in the project vicinity that, when combined with the Proposed Project, would result in a cumulatively considerable effect on the environment. Therefore, this exception does not apply to the project.
  3. Significant Effect. The Proposed Project site and surrounding neighborhood are located within an urbanized area, and no work is proposed offsite that could result in impacts to sensitive vegetation or other environmentally sensitive areas as a result of the Proposed Project. As such, there is nothing unusual about the project site or surrounding area. Furthermore, there is nothing unusual about the design of the Proposed Project that could result in a significant effect on the environment due to unusual circumstances. Therefore, there is no reasonable possibility that the Proposed Project would have a significant effect on the environment due to unusual circumstances, and this exception does not apply to the project.
  4. Scenic Highways. The project would not result in the demolition of existing structures or the construction of new facilities that would directly or indirectly affect an officially designated scenic highway or scenic resources near a scenic highway. There are no designated scenic resources or highways within ¼ mile of the project site and the site is not visible from any designated scenic highways. Therefore, this exception does not apply to the project.
  5. Hazardous Waste Sites. There are no District school facilities located on a hazardous waste site that is included on any list compiled pursuant to Section 65962.5 of the Government Code. Furthermore, no hazardous waste sites were identified within a quarter of a mile of the project site during review of the ENVIROSTOR database managed by the Department of Toxic Substances Control (DTSC) (DTSC 2018a).
  6. Historical Resources. According to the CEQA Guidelines regarding historical resources, a substantial adverse change in the significance of a historical resource amounts to a significant impact on the environment (Guidelines § 15064.5(b)). Accordingly, a substantial adverse change means demolition, destruction, relocation, or alteration of the resource or its immediate surroundings resulting in the significance of the resource being materially impaired. The project site is not a designated historical resource. However, because the school was built over 50 years ago, it embodies the potential for eligibility as a historical resource for purposes of CEQA. However, the proposed execution of a lease agreement, repairs to existing fascia and gutters, and placement of a modular building would not result in permanent modifications to existing structures that would materially alter the physical characteristics of the building. Therefore, this exception does not apply to the project. Additionally, the likelihood of impacting either prehistoric or historic archaeological resources is negligible for the current undertaking because grading and trenching into non-native soils is not proposed.

Approval of this item approves the Project as described and authorizes and directs staff to file a Notice of Exemption with the San Diego County Recorder/Clerk.

Whole Site Modernization Project (WSM) and related site construction and lease agreement at District-owned property at 3420 and 3430 Camino Del Rio North, San Diego, CA 92108, is exempt from further environmental review Pursuant to California Environmental Quality Act Guidelines (CEQA) Section 15301, and direct staff to file the Notice of Exemption (NOE) with the San Diego County Recorder/Clerk and California Office of Planning and Research State Clearinghouse.

4. Adopt Resolution Accepting Student Success Program, Inc's Contribution Toward Tenant Improvements.

 

FISCAL IMPACT: Total not-to-exceed amount of $4,061,350.00 consisting of $4,061,300.00 (contract amount) and $50.00 (Notice of Exemption filing fee).  Budget string: 9008-90405-00-6200-8500-0000-21400-8665 -Proposition Z Funds. BACKGROUND: The District expended Proposition Z bond funds to acquire the real property located at 3420 and 3430 Camino del Rio North, San Diego, CA 92108, also known as "Riverbank Property" for Students for Success Program, Inc. in order to provide facilities for students attending Audeo Charter School. The district and Student Success Program, Inc. need to construct certain structural upgrades, code requirements, and tenant improvements (collectively as "the Project") on the Riverbank Property. However, the district does not have sufficient Proposition Z bond funds allocated to construct the Project per the City of San Diego-approved construction documents. The budget shortfall is currently One Hundred Thousand Dollars ($100,000), which includes a ten percent contingency. To facilitate completion of the Project, Student Success Program, Inc. has offered to contribute to the Project for the specific purpose of augmenting the District's Project budget ("Contribution"). As provided for in the Resolution, Student Success Program, Inc. will issue a check or wire funds payable to "San Diego Unified School District" for One Hundred Thousand Dollars ($100,000) within seven days after the Board's award of the contract to the lowest responsive, responsible bidder, provided that any unused Contribution funds be returned to Student Success Program, Inc., and that the Contribution will not be used by the district unless all Proposition Z funds have been exhausted for the Project. 

 

Pursuant to Public Contract Code section 20111(b), the district must publicly competitively bid any public project involving an expenditure of $15,000 or more. The notice calling for bids was published once a week for two successive weeks in accordance with Public Contract Code section 20112.

 

Bids were due and opened on April 3, 2018. The district received a total of six (6) bids from M.A. Stevens Construction, Inc., SOLPAC CONSTRUCTION INC. dba Soltek Pacific Construction Company, Team C Construction, Straight Line General Contractors, Inc., Straub Construction, Inc. and USS Cal Builders Inc.

 

After evaluating the bids, staff determined M.A. Stevens Construction, Inc. to be the lowest responsive and responsible bidder. Additionally, consistent with the May 10, 2011 board approved resolution in support of service-disabled veteran-owned businesses (SDVOB) and disabled veteran business enterprises (DVBE) which established a 3 percent required participation of DVBE’s for all district construction contracting opportunities. The recommended contractor, M.A. Stevens Construction, Inc. submitted a 8.06 percent DVBE participation in its bid.

 

Environmental Review:

The Project is for the beneficial occupancy of Audeo Charter School, which is operated by Student Success Program, Inc. The school site is located at 3430 Camino Del Rio North, San Diego, CA 92108, and Project consists of a whole site modernization of the one existing building, but is not limited to, selective demolition, structural improvements, temporary shoring, limited exterior envelope work, new floor plan layouts, new ceilings, new lighting, new mechanical, plumbing, and electrical systems, and other improvements as indicated. The scope also includes interior and exterior accessibility improvements required to comply with the 2010 ADA Standards for Accessible Design and the accessibility requirements of the 2013 California Building Code.

 

The Project is subject to the requirements of the California Environmental Quality Act (CEQA), Public Resources Code (PRC) section 21000 et. seq., and its implementing Guidelines (California Code of Regulations, Title 14, Division 6, Chapter 3, sections 15000 et. seq., as amended). However, it is exempt from further environmental review under the following CEQA categorical exemption class:

 

Existing Facilities (Class 1) - Class 1 consists of the operation, repair, maintenance, permitting, leasing, licensing, or minor alteration of existing public or private structures, facilities, mechanical equipment, or topographical features, involving negligible or no expansion of use beyond that existing at the time of the lead agency's determination. Examples include, but are not limited to, [a] Interior or exterior alterations involving such things as interior partitions, plumbing, and electrical conveyances; [d] Restoration or rehabilitation of deteriorated or damaged structures, facilities, or mechanical equipment to meet current standards of public health and safety, unless it is determined that the damage was substantial and resulted from an environmental hazard such as earthquake, landslide, or flood (CEQA Guidelines §15301 [a] [d]).

 

The Project involves interior and exterior alterations to an existing operational facility, in addition to rehabilitation of structures and facilities to meet current standards of public health and safety. Rehabilitation activities include seismic upgrades to strengthen the building’s foundation and improvements to the Project site to comply with accessibility requirements of the 2010 ADA and the accessibility requirements of the most recent California Building Code. Use of the Project site as a resource center by the Charter School consists of a negligible expansion of use as described in the analysis below. Therefore, the application of a Class 1 categorical exemption is appropriate for the Project.

 

Section 15300.2 of the State CEQA Guidelines specifies several exceptions to the use of a categorical exemption as described below:

 

(a) Location. Classes 3, 4, 5, 6, and 11 are qualified by consideration of where the project is to be located – a project that is ordinarily insignificant in its impact on the environment may, in a particularly sensitive environment, be significant. Therefore, these classes are considered to apply in all instances, except where the project may impact on an environmental resource of hazardous or critical concern where designated, precisely mapped, and officially adopted pursuant to law by federal, state, or local agencies.

 

(b) Cumulative Impact. All exemptions for these classes are inapplicable when the cumulative impact of successive projects of the same type in the same place, over time is significant.

 

(c) Significant Effect. A categorical exemption shall not be used for an activity where there is a reasonable possibility that the activity will have a significant effect on the environment due to unusual circumstances.

 

(d) Scenic Highways. A categorical exemption shall not be used for a project which may result in damage to scenic resources including, but not limited to, trees, historic buildings, rock outcroppings, or similar resources within a highway officially designated as a state scenic highway. This does not apply to improvements that are required as mitigation by an adopted negative declaration or certified EIR.

 

(e) Hazardous Waste Sites. A categorical exemption shall not be used for a project located on a site that is included on any list compiled pursuant to Section 65962.5 of the Government Code.

 

(f) Historical Resources. A categorical exemption shall not be used for a project that may cause a substantial adverse change in the significance of a historical resource.

 

The Project does not have the potential to trigger any of the exceptions identified in CEQA Guidelines §15300.2 prohibiting the use of a categorical exemption as described below:

 

(a) Location. The proposed interior and exterior alterations will occur within the existing footprint of a developed site. Environmental conditions within and surrounding the project site consist of disturbed grounds that are not considered as environmentally sensitive areas. Minor ground disturbances such as foundation system improvements, compaction grouting, and hardscape and landscape improvements will occur within the existing site and do not pose significant impacts to offsite resources. Execution of the future lease agreement between the District and the Charter School and operation of the Charter School resource center would not drastically change operations of the site when compared with past commercial uses. All activity would be contained within the existing site. The Project will not impact environmentally sensitive areas or an environmental resource of hazardous or critical concern. No trees are proposed for removal. Therefore, this exception does not apply to the Project.

 

(b) Cumulative Impact. No future projects are planned for the project site. Any future site specific projects or changes in use of the project site undertaken by the Charter School or the District would require subsequent CEQA analysis and approval by the District Board. Future Capital Improvement Projects by the City of San Diego have been identified along Camino Del Rio North and South such as Water Group 968 pipe replacement to the east, Water Group Job 948 VC sewer mains south of Interstate 8, and New Street Lights project to the west. Construction and operation Project will not result in any significant cumulative impacts in combination with City of San Diego Capital Improvement Projects as these projects will occur outside the boundaries of the project site and will be implemented on separate schedules. Furthermore, the Project would not result in any significant impacts, that when combined with other cumulative projects, would be cumulatively considerable. Therefore, this exception does not apply to the Project.

 

(c) Significant Effect. The proposed construction activities are not considered an unusual circumstance as these activities are seen as standard maintenance of building facilities. The proposed improvements to the existing buildings are necessary to meet current standards for public health and safety. Such activities are not considered as an unusual circumstance as these activities do not include specifications that would be considered out of the ordinary.

 

Execution of the lease agreement between the District and the Charter School and operation of the proposed resource center would not drastically change operations of the site when compared with past commercial uses. There would be no new playgrounds or other noise generating uses that would be different than prior use of the site as commercial office space. Operations would be during the day, consistent with operation of a commercial office building. (The lease agreement will be brought to the Board for approval at a subsequent meeting in the future.)

 

Traffic impacts associated with the use of the project site by the Charter School would conservatively generate approximately 663 new daily trips, 4 new AM peak hour trips, and 64 new PM peak hour trips. Because the Project would not generate more than 1,000 daily trips or 100 peak -hour trips, a full traffic impact study for the Project is not warranted per the City’s Traffic Impact Study Manual, dated July 1998, and traffic impacts are not considered significant.

 

Parking requirements for the new resource center were determined based on consistency with the City of San Diego Municipal Code (Section 142.050 et seq.). Specifically, Table 142-05G specifies parking ratios for specified non-residential use. Given that the project site does not include traditional classrooms, parking rates for schools with grades 10 through 12 were used, which requires a parking rate of one parking space per five students. Because the new resource center conservatively assumes there would be 183 students on site at any given time, the Proposed Project would require approximately 37 parking spaces. The 123 existing parking spaces on the project site would exceed the 37 spaces required under the City of San Diego Municipal Code.

 

The Project will not impact environmentally sensitive areas or an environmental resource of hazardous or critical concern. No trees are proposed for removal. Therefore, this exception does not apply to the Project.

 

(d) Scenic Highways. The nearest highway is Interstate 8, approximately 375 feet south, and Interstate 15, approximately 2,100 feet northeast from the project site. Neither portions of Interstate 8 and Interstate 15 within the Project site are listed as an official designated scenic highway. A segment of Interstate 8, between State Route 125 and State Route 94, and a segment of Interstate 15, from State Route 76 north, are identified as an officially designated scenic highway and scenic route respectively (Caltrans, 2017; County of San Diego, 2017). Construction or operation of the Project would not involve activities that would directly or indirectly impact an officially designated highway or scenic resources near a scenic highway because there are no scenic highways deemed eligible or officially designated located within the immediate vicinity of the project site. Therefore, this exception does not apply to the Project.

 

(e) Hazardous Waste Sites. The Proposed Project is located within an existing, developed site that has not been identified as a hazardous waste site pursuant to Section 65962.5 of the Government Code (Geotracker, 2017). In addition, the alteration and improvement activities will remain within the property and will not involve heavy trenching or excavation. Therefore, this exception does not apply to the Project.

 

(f) Historical Resources. The Proposed Project consists of alterations and improvements to the existing buildings located at 3420 and 3430 Camino Del Rio North in San Diego. The existing buildings were constructed in 1979 and are not listed as a historic resource (City of San Diego, 2017). Therefore, the Proposed Project will occur within the existing, operational facility and will not cause a substantial adverse change in the significance of a historical resource. This exception does not apply to the Project.

 

Approval of this item approves the Project as described in the attached NOE, authorizes and directs staff to file a Notice of Exemption with the San Diego County Recorder/Clerk, awards the contract to M.A. Stevens Construction, Inc., and allows the District to accept $100,000.00 from Student Success Programs, Inc. to augment the District's Project budget to alleviate any shortfall, provided that any unused funds are returned.

IMPACT TO DISTRICT STAFFING: None. 

 

CONSULTATION WITH BOARD ADVISORY COMMITTEE: Not applicable.

 

BACKGROUND: In 2015, SDG&E offered a competitive selection process to school districts in San Diego County to partially fund a Zero Net Energy (ZNE) Pilot project. The district submitted a plan to SDG&E and included Vista Grande ES as the proposed ZNE site. The district was selected for the ZNE pilot. The pilot program is managed by the district’s Energy Utilities Program (EUP) Team. The ZNE Vista Grande ES project is primarily funded by Proposition 39, the Clean Energy Jobs Act passed by voters in 2012. Proposition 39 funding is limited to K-14 school districts energy efficiency projects.

 

Partial funding of the SDG&E ZNE Pilot Program is provided by the SDG&E energy savings incentive program known as “Savings by Design”. The Savings by Design team works with the District’s EUP program team to design the best energy ZNE project. The sequence to the Savings by Design (SBD) process is as follows:

 

  • District applies for the SDG&E SBD program;
  • District’s EUP Program team works with SDG&E SBD program to audit and model the Vista Grande ES site;
  • The District’s EUP team develops an Energy Efficiency Plan for the Californian Energy Commission (CEC) approval;
  • Prop 39 funds for the Vista Grande ES site are transferred to the district prior to an RFP;
  • The Solar portion of the ZNE plan is excluded from the calculation of all of the projects (i.e. new chiller, air handlers, controls and LED lighting are the remaining energy savings measures funded by the SDG&E SBD agreement);
  • Once the energy savings analysis is completed, SDG&E SBD proposes an energy savings incentive plan as part of an SBD agreement. The SBD agreement is approved by the district Board of Education;
  • District contracts a selected RFP firm to build the energy efficiency projects at Vista Grande ES;
  • SDG&E pays the district based on the performance of energy savings after the site is upgraded (amount paid to the district is based on the approved SDG&E SBD agreement);
  • SDG&E sends the SBD incentive check to the district to be deposited into the Prop 39 restricted fund to cover the remaining costs for the ZNE project;
  • Final project report for the CEC is required to be completed prior to June 30, 2020.

 

This project will save energy whereby reducing the cost of electricity to the district. This Agreement is a one-time incentive (revenue) the district will receive from SDG&E, which may be adjusted to reflect actual performance of the project.

RECOMMENDATION: Approve Agreement with Cherwell Software, LLC for the purchase of a help desk problem management system software with installation, configuration, and support (SW-18-0525-28). Authorize the execution of any documents necessary to effectuate this Agreement. The term of this Agreement is May 16, 2018 through May 14, 2023.

 

FISCAL IMPACT: Total not-to-exceed amount: $476,750.00.

Budget Strings: 

5538-90403-00-5841-8500-0000-21400-8641 License

5538-90403-00-6214-8500-0000-21400-8641 Installation, Configuration, Support

 

PRIOR YEAR FISCAL IMPACT: The current system has no cost due to the age of the system.

 

IMPACT TO DISTRICT STAFFING: None

 

CONSULTATION WITH BOARD ADVISORY COMMITTEE: Not applicable.

 

BACKGROUND: On November 16, 2017 the district received three Proposals from Cherwell Software, LLC, Freshworks, Inc., and Network Consulting Services, Inc. in response to a Request for Proposal (RFP) issued on October 17, 2017. Based on the district evaluation committee's review, Cherwell Software, LLC is recommended for award to provide the district with a Help Desk Problem Management system software including installation, configuration, and support.

 

The IT Department Help Desk software currently in place (Remedy) has been unsupported for over a decade. Because technology has exponentially changed in the last few years, the version of Remedy that the IT Help Desk uses is no longer a functional product for the agents taking and handling calls or for staff attempting to submit tickets for service.

 

The Cherwell Help Desk system will modernize how service is provided to our schools and support staff, will help to decrease wait/response times, and offers features such as:

• Automated Self-Service Portal - allows users to reset their own passwords and report and monitor their own tickets;
• Access to built-in knowledge database - provides Knowledge Centered Management allowing help desk and customer searches for simple online solutions to technical issues;
• Chat agent - allows real-time interaction with Help Desk support staff for quick answers to their questions;
• Customer Survey - allows the Help Desk to stay connected to changing customer needs;
• Flexibility to work on multiple devices - provides access to the service management system from any device (pc, mac, laptop, tablet, iPad, and smartphones).

 

The Cherwell Help Desk system will also provide the IT Department with additional industry best practices of ITIL-standards-based functions and processes including Change Management and Problem Management.

 

Additionally, the system will provide the Help Desk staff and IT management built-in Analytics and Dashboards to accurately measure service quality and quantity and allow them to efficiently adjust to critical support needs/trends.
